A few days ago, I made one of the biggest mistakes a filmmaker can make.

While cleaning up my Samsung T7 1TB SSD, I accidentally deleted around 100GB of footage that I actually needed. The moment I realized what I'd done, my heart sank. If you're a filmmaker, photographer, or content creator, you probably know that feeling.

Hours of work. Gone.

At first, I thought I'd lost everything. But after a lot of research, patience, and a few stressful hours, I managed to recover most of the footage and even repair the files that seemed completely broken.

I'm writing this article because when I was searching for solutions, most of the guides I found were either too technical or didn't explain the entire process from start to finish. So here's exactly what worked for me.

The First Thing I Did

The second I realized the footage was gone, I stopped using the SSD completely.

This is probably the most important step in the entire recovery process.

When you delete a file, it isn't actually removed immediately. Your computer simply marks that space as "available" for new data. If you keep using the drive, new files can overwrite the deleted data, and once that happens, recovery becomes much harder or even impossible.

So I immediately disconnected my Samsung T7 SSD from my Mac and connected it to my Windows PC.

